- body: {"id":"chatcmpl-a022f8feac0733d3","object":"chat.completion","created":1782674245,"model":"nemotron-3-super","choices":[{"index":0,"message":{"role":"assistant","content":"\n\n**LangChain4j Tool Calling (Function Calling) – Summary of Guidance**\n\nLangChain4j provides a unified way to enable LLMs to invoke developer-defined tools (functions) when needed. The feature is supported by LLMs that have been fine-tuned for tool usage (not all models support it equally well).\n\n### Core Concept\n- The LLM does **not** execute the tool itself; instead, it outputs a structured request indicating the tool to call and the arguments.\n- The developer must then execute the tool (e.g., call a Java method, invoke an API) and return the result to the LLM via a `ToolExecutionResultMessage`.\n- This enables the LLM to perform actions like calculations, web searches, sending emails, etc., by delegating to the appropriate tool.\n\n### Two Levels of Abstraction\n1. **Low‑level API** – Direct use of `ChatModel`/`StreamingChatModel` and `ToolSpecification`.\n2. **High‑level API** – AI Services with `@Tool`‑annotated Java methods (recommended for most use cases).\n\n### Key Steps (Low‑Level)\n1. **Define the tool** – Create a `ToolSpecification` that includes:\n   - Tool name\n   - Clear description (what the tool does and when to use it)\n   - Parameter schema (name, type, description, required flags) using `JsonObjectSchema`.\n   - Optional metadata (e.g., for Anthropic or MCP providers).\n\n   ```java\n   ToolSpecification toolSpec = ToolSpecification.builder()\n       .name(\"getWeather\")\n       .description(\"Returns the weather forecast for a given city\")\n       .parameters(JsonObjectSchema.builder()\n           .addStringProperty(\"city\", \"The city for which the weather forecast should be returned\")\n           .addEnumProperty(\"temperatureUnit\", List.of(\"CELSIUS\", \"FAHRENHEIT\"))\n           .required(\"city\")\n           .build())\n       .build();\n   ```\n\n   Alternatively, generate specs from a class or object:\n   ```java\n   List<ToolSpecification> specs = ToolSpecifications.toolSpecificationsFrom(WeatherTools.class);\n   ```\n\n2. **Send a chat request with tools**:\n   ```java\n   ChatRequest request = ChatRequest.builder()\n       .messages(UserMessage.from(\"What will the weather be like in London tomorrow?\"))\n       .toolSpecifications(List.of(toolSpec))\n       .build();\n   ChatResponse response = model.chat(request);\n   AiMessage aiMessage = response.aiMessage();\n   ```\n\n3. **Handle tool execution requests**:\n   - If `aiMessage.hasToolExecutionRequests()` is true, extract each `ToolExecutionRequest`.\n   - Execute the corresponding tool (e.g., call your Java method) with the provided arguments.\n   - Build a `ToolExecutionResultMessage` for each request and send it back in a follow‑up chat request:\n     ```java\n     String result = ...; // result of executing the tool\n     ToolExecutionResultMessage resultMsg = ToolExecutionResultMessage.from(toolExecutionRequest, result);\n     ChatRequest followUp = ChatRequest.builder()\n         .messages(List.of(userMessage, aiMessage, resultMsg))\n         .toolSpecifications(List.of(toolSpec))\n         .build();\n     ChatResponse finalResponse = model.chat(followUp);\n     ```\n\n4. **Streaming** – Use `StreamingChatModel` and implement `StreamingChatResponseHandler` to receive `onPartialToolCall` and `onCompleteToolCall` callbacks.\n\n### High‑Level (AI Services)\n- Define an interface with methods annotated with `@Tool` (and optionally `@P` for parameter descriptions).\n- Create an instance via `AiServices.create(...)`. The LLM will automatically invoke the annotated methods when it decides to use a tool.\n- This approach hides the low‑level message‑passing details.\n\n### Best Practices\n- **Clarity** – Provide unambiguous tool names, descriptions, and parameter descriptions. If a human can understand the tool, the LLM is more likely to use it correctly.\n- **Model support** – Not all LLMs support tools; check the “Tools” column in the model compatibility list (available in the docs).\n- **Tool vs. JSON mode** – Tool calling is distinct from JSON mode; the former is for invoking functions, the latter for constraining output to JSON.\n- **Multimodal results** – `ToolExecutionResultMessage` can include non‑text content (images, etc.) but provider support varies.\n- **Metadata** – Can be added to `ToolSpecification` and forwarded to providers that support it (currently Anthropic by default; MCP tool provider can include MCP‑specific metadata).\n\n### Sources\n- Official tutorial: https://docs.langchain4j.dev/tutorials/tools/\n- GitHub source (same content): https://github.com/langchain4j/langchain4j/blob/main/docs/docs/tutorials/tools.md\n\nThese sources cover the full details, including code examples for manual tool spec creation, using `ChatModel`, streaming, and the high‑level AI Services approach.","refusal":null,"annotations":null,"audio":null,"function_call":null,"tool_calls":[],"reasoning":"We have fetched the documentation from the official LangChain4j tutorials page and the GitHub markdown file. The content is extensive and covers the tool-calling (function calling) feature.\n\nWe need to summarize the relevant guidance with source URLs.\n\nKey points from the documentation:\n\n1. **Concept**: Tools (function calling) allow LLMs to trigger actions by expressing intent to call a tool (defined by the developer) in their response. The developer then executes the tool and returns the result to the LLM.\n\n2. **Two levels of abstraction**:\n   - **Low-level**: Using `ChatModel` and `ToolSpecification` APIs.\n   - **High-level**: Using AI Services and `@Tool`-annotated Java methods.\n\n3. **Creating Tool Specifications**:\n   - Manually via `ToolSpecification.builder()`.\n   - Using helper methods: `ToolSpecifications.toolSpecificationsFrom(Class)`, `ToolSpecifications.toolSpecificationsFrom(Object)`, `ToolSpecifications.toolSpecificationFrom(Method)`.\n\n4. **Using ChatModel (low-level)**:\n   - Build a `ChatRequest` with messages and `toolSpecifications`.\n   - If the LLM decides to call a tool, the `AiMessage` will contain `toolExecutionRequests`.\n   - Developer must execute the tool(s) and then create a `ToolExecutionResultMessage` to send back to the LLM.\n\n5. **Using StreamingChatModel**: Similar but with callbacks for partial and complete tool calls.\n\n6. **High-level AI Services**: Not detailed in the fetched snippet but mentioned. Typically, you define an interface with methods annotated with `@Tool` and then create an instance of that interface via `AiServices.create(...)`.\n\n7. **Best practices**:\n   - Provide clear and unambiguous tool name, description, and parameter descriptions.\n   - Not all LLMs support tools; check the \"Tools\" column in the models list.\n   - Tools/function calling is not the same as JSON mode.\n\n8. **Multimodal tool results**: `ToolExecutionResultMessage` can carry non-text content (images, etc.) but provider support varies.\n\n9. **Metadata**: Can be included in `ToolSpecification` and sent to LLM providers that support it (currently only Anthropic module by default, but MCP tool provider can include MCP-specific metadata).\n\nWe should summarize the guidance and provide the source URLs.\n\nThe two main sources we fetched are:\n- https://docs.langchain4j.dev/tutorials/tools/\n- https://github.com/langchain4j/langchain4j/blob/main/docs/docs/tutorials/tools.md\n\nBoth are essentially the same content (the tutorial page is likely generated from the markdown). We can cite both or just the official docs.\n\nLet's craft a summary.\n\n"},"logprobs":null,"finish_reason":"stop","stop_reason":null,"token_ids":null}],"service_tier":null,"system_fingerprint":null,"usage":{"prompt_tokens":7118,"total_tokens":8726,"completion_tokens":1608,"prompt_tokens_details":null},"prompt_logprobs":null,"prompt_token_ids":null,"kv_transfer_params":null}

